social_posts.post_text: Over the moon to see this piece that I made in the stunning home of @alexisforeman 🖤

If I was to summarize 2022 in 3 words it would be Home, Family & Growth.

Home. We sold our apartment, renovated and moved into our house. The kids love running around in the backyard, painting and playing with playdoh in the basement and hanging out in our new neighborhood. I look forward to more laughter, play and new memories in our beloved home.

Family. Like my wife @carolinastorm wrote in her year in review, our oldest son was diagnosed with autism in the beginning of this year. I remember Carolina bringing this up a few years ago, and I dismissed it due to poor knowledge about autism. How could he be autistic, he has such a sparkling personality, remembers songs & tv episodes right away & shows so much affection for his family? This is still true - but as time went on, it became clear that his social communication wasn’t at the same level as his peers, and that he sometimes got VERY upset when we did something different or broke our normal patterns. We’ve been very privileged to be able to bring onboard amazing coaches that have helped him significantly - and we’re constantly learning how we can support him better. Like any child; if you love them unconditionally, pay them a lot of attention, encourage them and give them certain tools they’ll blossom.

Growth. This year my artistic endeavor really took a leap forward, I experimented more, painted more and had my first solo vernissage that sold out(!). I also decided to leave Spotify to join a private equity firm part time. I’m learning so much and having a lot of fun! I’m also starting up a new project. Like I mentioned, we’ve been very privileged to being able to help Tom thanks to the best coaches, but a lot of that information is not accessible. So me and Carolina are spending time with experts to figure out how we can bring this knowledge to millions of parents and make it affordable. More to come!

When it comes to 2023, I hope to continue on the trajectory we’re on, making family #1 priority and continue to learn + create. I’m excited for what the new year will bring and grateful for the year that we’ve had ❤️

Paris. It makes me so happy to see one of my paintings in the master bedroom of this spectacular Parisian apartment, just around the corner from the Eiffel Tower. I’m very grateful that the owners allowed me to share a few pictures from their stunning home 🖤

Had a lot of fun this week attending a few Stockholm Design Week events together with @carolinastorm .

We had the pleasure to meet old friends and new interesting people, and like in a lot of networking situations, people ask you what you work with. And when I reply “I split my time between being an abstract painter and working in Private Equity” people usually have a few follow up questions 😅

Do you aim to only focus on your art? Those seem completely polar opposite, why that set up? 

People didn’t seem to think it was as strange when I worked at Spotify (music is creative), although I was only focused on growing the business.

I’ve come to really love this setup, part of what I do is highly commercial and logical and the other part is very creative and intuitive. There’s also very little cross-over, so when I’m painting, I’m not thinking about PE, and the other way around.

After talking to people about this for a few minutes, I can tell that many have a spark, “what if I could be a photographer and a chef, a lawyer and a baker” etc etc.

There’s too much pressure in society that you need to pick one thing, to be a doctor/lawyer/writer/artist and I think it can make people feel somewhat claustrophobic as it might not reflect their main sets of interests.

It would be interesting to hear your reflections on this, and how you balance your “real work” with things you care deeply about.

Our vacation has come to an end and on Monday we’re back to the daycare & work routine. I'm an optimistic person, but I didn't have high expectations for this summer. I knew that I had to work on and off throughout most of the summer, while juggling two kids at home - how would that go?!

Before our eldest son got his diagnosis, we couldn't understand how people could be in a car or plane with a small child for more than 10-15 minutes without them going completely nuclear - it made a lot more sense when we finally understood that we had/have a different experience. So we've been anything but adventurous these last few years.

That really changed this summer. Our dear friends Benedetta & Gilles spent the summer in Italy, so we borrowed their cargo bike - this was the catalyst for us to start making daily mini-adventures around Stockholm, exploring lakes, new parks, and areas we haven't been to before. Both kids really loved it!

After a few weeks, we felt way more brave than before and rented a house on Dalarö, in the archipelago. We spent our days on the beach, jumping in muddy puddles (go Swedish summers) and exploring. Things didn't always go great. It's pretty clear that Tom needs to relax between 1-3 PM and have a massive snack, otherwise he'll likely have meltdowns. Also, traveling very early in the morning is way better than later.

After that big adventure (for us), we spontaneously rented a house on Gotland, where we spent a week with my brother & his lovely family. We couldn't have had a better time; exploring the island, eating food, and playing by the beach. Even the 3-hour boat ride went well!

I'm so happy and grateful for this summer. I hope we'll continue to stretch our comfort zone throughout this year while making room for everyone's different needs to feel good.

After a board meeting at a company I’m engaged with, a gentleman I hadn’t previously met approached me with an unexpected topic: my art. While it’s not unusual for colleagues to notice or purchase my work, each acknowledgment is a pleasant nod to my dual life as an artist.

Over several weeks, we discussed various pieces until he selected a recently shared canvas—a visual symphony of blues, embodying both movement and varying depths.

He acquired it, and soon, this piece will make its journey to its new home in Dubai, set in an oak frame. It’s always gratifying to see my art finding new homes, subtly bridging my role in private equity with my passion for painting.

Today is a special day as we celebrate the launch of my incredibly talented wife @carolinastorm’s collaboration with @layered_official. Carolina’s keen eye for detail shines through in her curation of colors for the Somerset sofa collection. Drawing inspiration from the iconic Charleston Farmhouse, she has managed to create a line that harmonizes the practical and the beautiful. I’ve watched her put her heart and soul into this project, and to see it come to fruition—in our own living room no less—is exhilarating. Proud and overjoyed would be an understatement. Visit Layered.se to see this extraordinary collection for yourself.

Yesterday at the playground, James was inconsolable, grappling with icy hands yet refusing to wear his gloves. 🥶 It makes me yearn for the warmth of o summer, or at least a more pleasant autumn—with gloves on, of course.

Excited to announce my upcoming solo exhibition, ‘Echoes of Motion,’ in collaboration with @Collection_Apart. After the success of ‘We Move Lightly,’ which sold out in a mere 72 hours, I can’t wait to share my newest works.

If you’re in Stockholm, it would mean the world to me to see you at the opening night. For those who can’t join us in person, don’t worry; we’ll be sharing photos of all artworks online and shipping is available worldwide.

Save the Date: Opening on 17th November, 16:00 - 19:30. 
RSVP at mail@collectionapart.com
Location: Collection apart, Renstiernas Gata 13, 116 28, Stockholm
Exhibition runs from 17th - 20th November

The greatest compliment for me comes when @carolinastorm, wants to keep one of my paintings and finds a special place for it in our home. 

As an artist, I generally don’t believe in holding onto too many of my works. 

While I’m painting, I don’t like to think that I’ll keep the piece or even sell it, it would add too much pressure to the creative process.

The decision of whether to keep or sell a piece becomes apparent only once it’s complete. For me, the real joy in painting lies in the journey of creation — exploring, experimenting, and letting my intuition guide me. 

Yet, occasionally, it’s rewarding to retain a piece. I’m thankful to Carolina for persuading me not to sell this painting.

Reflecting on the past year, 2023 has been filled with home, growth, and purpose.

Settling in Enskede has been delightful, especially getting to know our community. Our new cargo bike has been a hit with the kids, turning daycare pickups into exciting adventures.

In my Private Equity career, I’m 14 months in and loving it. I’m thankful for my brilliant colleagues and love learning about such a broad range of companies.

Artistically, painting has become a significant part of my life. I’ve dedicated a day each week to this passion, leading to a lovely exhibition at @collection_apart, where I sold all my works. Thank you all for the kind words of encouragement!

Our family life has also seen remarkable growth. With the help of an autism coach, we’ve been supporting our son Tom in developing new skills. The progress he’s made is astounding. This year, we also ventured on family trips to Dalarö and Gotland. We had a lot of anxiety prior to the trips but it’s been incredibly fulfilling and showed us the value of stepping out of our comfort zone.

2023 was also a year of purpose. Sharing our journey with Tom’s autism has connected us with many who have similar experiences. I’ve also joined the board of @tiimoapp, a visual planning app for neurodivergent individuals, and I’m thrilled to contribute to such a meaningful cause.

I couldn’t be prouder of my wife @carolinastorm for her achievements this year, including launching a newsletter and her collection for @layered_official. Her effort & dedication has truly been inspiring.

Can’t help to feel very thankful for the fact that my family is safe with everything going on in the world. I hope that 2024 brings more peace and stability in the world.

Thanks to everyone who’s been a part of our journey this year. Looking forward to more growth, purpose, and joy in 2024! ❤️
